<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Evidence Submitted by Lumos</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence Submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">Lumos </span></h1><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">About Lumos</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Lumos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is an international NGO</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> working to end the institutionalisation of children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> around the world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. We work to transform education, health and social care systems for children and their families and help children move from institutions to family-based care.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  We are a founding member of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UNICEF </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Global Partnership for Children with Di</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sabilities in Development.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.wearelumos.org"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.wearelumos.org</span></a></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">About our response</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This response is intended to highlight the impact of the systematic institutionalisation of children with disabilities around the world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  It </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">illustr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the need for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and other donors to adopt a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">approach </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which is consistent both with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">international human rights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commitments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">international good practice in the provision of and transition to community and family based care for childr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en with disabilities.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nquiry is a timely opportunity to ensure that the current process to replace the Millennium Development Goals puts in place specific mechanisms for the protection of societies’ most vulnerable children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> those with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and living in institutional care. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst much of the evidence and research we refer to comes from the European Region, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">issues raised are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> common to children everywhere.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The Impact of Institutionalisation on Children’s Health, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Development and Well</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">-being</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">An estimated 8 million children worldwide live in some form of institutionalised residential care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  Research from across the world has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">demonstrate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">significant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">harm caused </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">institutionalisation.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he harmful effects include: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Impaired early brain development, leading to delayed cognitive and physical development and, in some cases, resulting in the onset of an intellectual disability; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35.7pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Attachment disorders, which may result in the development of autistic behaviours, self-stimulation, self-harming, aggression to others or cruelty to animals; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Poor cognitive processing, resulting in educational under-achievement; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Poor physical health, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ncluding chronic infections; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Non-organic failure to thrive; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Unusually raised anxieties, specifically the fear of being abandoned and the fear of being alone, resulting in nightmares and sleeping disorders; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Eating disorders;</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Enuresis; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Difficulty un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">derstanding right from wrong, resulting in behaviour such as lying and stealing; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Difficulties in forming healthy emotional relationships as adults; </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Increased risk of child abuse and neglect; and significantly reduced life chances and, in some cases, li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fe expectancy.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 27.91pt; padding-left:7.79pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Disabled children in institutional care are particularly vulnerable to more severe forms of violence, abuse and poor quality, depersonalised care.</span></li></ul><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Disability and Children</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">: An International Development Priority</span></h1><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">The international </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">rights fra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">mework</span></h2><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UNCRC: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The Convention on the Rights of the Child sets the international standard regarding the rights of all children.  It contains specific standards on h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ealth, education, legal, civil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">and social services.  At its very core is the principle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> best interests of the child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> must be maintained at all times. Ev</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ery child has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the right to life, survival and to develop to their true potential.  These rights have particular resonance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for children with disabilities and institutionalised children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h3><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UNCR</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">PD: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">affirms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> among others</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the specific rights of children with disabilities (Article 7);</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the right to live independently and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> be included in the community (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Article 19); the right to personal mobility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">(Article 20); the right to habilitation and rehabilitation (Article 26); the right to participate in political and public life (Article 29)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. All of these articles are particularly of relevance to institutionalised children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. Article 32 of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the UNCRPD stipulates that international aid must </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">be in compliance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Convention. It is therefore vital that the replacement for the MDGs is fully in line with the provisions of the CRPD and specifically addresses the needs and rights of children wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">th disabilities. </span></h3><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">   </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Regional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Agreements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The World Health O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">rganiz</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ation’s Better Health, Better Lives Initiative was launched in 2008. The initiative aim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> to: “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">nsure that all children and young people with intellectual disabilities are fully </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">participating members of society, living with their families, integrated in the community and receiving health care and support proportional to their needs.”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The Initiative takes a holistic approach to the health, development and well-being of children wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">h intellectual disabilities and the role of different agencies to achieve this.  </span></h3><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n 2010 the European Declaration and Action Plan on the Health of Children and Young People with Intellectual Disabilities and their Families was signed on behalf of 53 Minis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ters of Health of the European region</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, including the United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. The Declaration was formally endorsed as a Resolution in 2011.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">It</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> goes some way to bridging the potential gap on the rights of children with disabilities in particular</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and details the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ter-connected rights of children to live with their families </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> access appropriate health and education services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> participate fully in the community, live with dignity and achieve independence.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> It is just one example of a model for how the CRPD can be promoted and implemented at the global and regional levels. </span></h3><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Disabled children,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> institutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold"> and international development</span></h2><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Worldwide, many children with disabilities are placed in institutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> (som</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">etimes labelled ‘orphanages’)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> that do not meet their needs which are often located a considerable distance from their families. Growing up in an institution denies children individual love and care and can damage their brain development. When they leave in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">stitutions research shows that they are 10 times more likely than their peers to be involved in prostitution, 40 times more likely to have a criminal record and 500 times more likely to commit suicide.</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.5pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Institutionalisation exacerbates and causes disabilit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">y, further disadvantaging and marginalising children with disabilities. This makes it harder for international and national development policies and programmes to reach children with disabilities than their peers who were not institutionalised.  In additio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n by virtue of living in an institution, excluded from society, the views and needs of children with disabilities are often not taken into account when important political and policy decisions are mad</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e concerning them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Consequently their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> needs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">go </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">unresearched</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and their poverty goes unmonitored</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  This is exacerbated by the conspicuous absence of disability among the targets and indicators of the Millennium Development Goals.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  </span></h3><h3 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2.2.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Evidence from around the world confirms that disabled children, living in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> institutions are at particular risk of harm and are especially vulnerable to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">violence and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">abuse. The Council of Europe found this to be due to “a pervasive culture of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">depersonalisation,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> lack of privacy, inadequate food, feeding and poorly trained staff”</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  As outlined in paragraph 4.2, children with severe disabilities in institutions are at risk of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">malnutrition and neglect as a direct result of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">care provided in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> institutional setting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">&#xa0;</span></h3><h3 style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">2.2.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Writing on the occasion of Universal Children’s Day on 20 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">November</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Kirsten Sandberg, Chairperson of the UN Committee on the Rights of the Child, Marta Santos Pais, Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General on Violence against Children and three other senior UN representatives called for child prote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ction to be prioritised in the post 2015 agenda; </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> They </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">stressed,  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">“The post-2015 development agenda should address inequalities that heighten the risks of violence, abuse and exploitation of children. Governments should meet their obligation to protect ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ildren from violence. [..] </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The post-2015 agenda should include a strategic goal and indicators on child protection </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">to prevent and address all forms of violence against girls and boys, and to bring to justice those responsible for these acts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> [..] We urge n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ational governments and the international community to support this process and to provide adequate resources to protect children from violence, abuse and exploitation, in development and emergency situations. Inclusive, sustainable and duly funded child p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">rotection systems should be establis</span><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">h</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ed in all countries, supported by sound investment in social protection programmes to address the root causes of child rights violations, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">to promote universal access to basic social services that help families care for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">and protect their children, and to safeguard the rights of children in need of assistance and alternative care.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> [..]” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">  </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">The Importance of Policy Coherence</span></h1><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Over the past half century, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> has engaged in a process of deinstitutionalisation, large segregated children’s homes have become a thing of the past. Disabled children and their families are supported so that they can remain together and services are provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> within the commun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ity.  This major shift in approach was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">in recognition that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the child’s best interest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> could not be served in an institutionalised setting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> It is important therefore that the UK’s international aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">should be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">uilt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> around the same core principle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> funds should only ever be used in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the best interest of the child</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">UK funds should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">not be used to renovate or build </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">institutions or orphanages – and should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">instead </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">be directed towards community and family bas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ed alternatives such as inclusive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">education, foster care, family support services and community health services.</span></h2><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The European Union in its recently approved Regulations for Structural Funds from 2014-2020 made strong </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">commitments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">that these EU funds should only be spent in line with the CRP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">D and that the funding of the transition from institutional to community based care should be prioritised. These rules effectively forbid the funds from being used to renovate or build new institutions.  This is a welcome precedent which is expected to inf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">luence other EU funding mechanisms including international development</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, given that the European Union has now ratified the CRPD and must meet its obligations under Article 32 to deliver an inclusive international development programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.  </span></h2><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Several bilateral </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">donor agencies have made strong commitments on disability in recent years including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, Ausaid, SIDA and USAID.   So</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">me funding streams, such as the November 2013 USAID’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">FY13 Disability Funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">programme, specifically rule out that funds can be used for institutionalisation or institutions for children or adults with disabilities.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Such a stipulation is not yet consistently included across other programmes. </span></h2><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Case Studies and Examples</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> of Deinstitu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">tionalisation</span></h1><h2 style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:13.5pt; margin:10pt 6pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In order to tackle the inequalities faced by children with disabilities who grow up in institutions Lumos has develo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ped a comprehensive model of de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">institutionalisation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">We have successfully demonstrated how this model can work in practice, fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">r example in our work in the Floresti region in Moldova. Lumos was instrumental in bringing together authorities and stakeholders at the regional and local level to implement a national action plan on reforming the residential child care system. Since 2007</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> two out of three residential institutions have been closed and in the remaining institution only 52 out of 289 children remain to be integrated into their communities. As part of the de-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">institutionalisation programme children have been re-integrated into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">their biological or extended families, into foster care or homes in the community. Inclusive education was also developed and children who used to live in residential institutions can now attend mainstream schools in their communities with multidisciplinar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">y support available to them and to the teaching staff.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">This example demonstrates that de-institutionalisation, inclusive education and re-integration into the community is possible even in relatively poor countries. Similar examples exist around the world</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h2><h2 style="background-color:#ffffff; line-height:13.5pt; margin:10pt 6pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">In Bulgaria Lumos identified that there were significant numbers of malnourished and undernourished children in life-threatening situations living in institutions. This was largely a consequence of the nature of institutionalisation. Some children with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">disabilities need particular, personalised, attention to help them eat and drink properly, the lack of this individual attention, communication and stimulation in the institution was shown to be affecting the development of these children.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">At the request </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">of the Government, and in partnership with them, Lumos intervened immediately: We assessed the specific nutritional needs of the children and offered institution staff specialist guidance on ensuring that children at risk were receiving enough nutrients vi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a food and drink. We then made comprehensive recommendations for improvements in the practical methods of feeding children and young people with disabilities and have been introducing the intensive interaction method to baby institutions in the country.  W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ithin six months of our intervention, mortality rates in those institutions had reduced by 90%.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">One of the challenges with international development work is how to make change sustainable for the future. In the case of Lumos’s work, the financial solution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> springs from the problem itself.  Large sums of money are often spent to improve institution buildings, but research shows this does not significantly improve outcomes for the children. There is also a common misconception that institutions are cheaper th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">an family and community-based care services. In fact, institutions are expensive to run. Because institutions provide 24-hour care, and because large buildings must be maintained, even those with extremely poor conditions are costly. Studies consistently s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">how that institutional care costs significantly more per child than family support services or foster care. Often a small intervention in a family can prevent a child from going into an institution. This is better for the child, but also saves the State th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">e cost of 18 years of institutional care. Outcomes for young people raised in care are so poor that the long-term cost to society is far greater than providing good quality community-based services. Reallocating budgets from institutional to community-base</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">d care can be difficult for some countries. However, Lumos’s experience shows that if an evidence-based deinstitutionalisation plan is used, governments can develop a range of new services that are financially sustainable - and these services cost no more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to run than residential institutions.</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Concluding Remarks</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> and Questions for the Inquiry</span></h1><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Lumos welcome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> opportunity to submit evidence to this Inquiry</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and the commitment shown by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> and other bilateral agencies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">to secure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> the inclusion of disability as a core issue in both the High Level Panel report and the Secretary General’s Report on the post 2015 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. We welcome </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">in particular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">the acknowledgment in these reports that international development should “leave no one</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> behind”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span></h2><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">It is our position that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">all international and national governmental and non-governmental agencies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">in their programmes, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">contribute to ceasing the use of institutions as an acceptable form of care for children with disabili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ties </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">:</span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Prevent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> admissions of children with disabilities to institutions – where their individual needs cannot be met.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Offer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> alternative care services that are family and community-based and provide for children’s individual needs</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Support</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inclusive education which is crucial to the success of deinstitutionalisation</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ensuring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the diversion of funds and resources from institutions to community based health, education and social services</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 38.41pt; padding-left:11.24pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Supporting  the dissemination and incorporation of good </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">practice examples of self-advocacy and participation of children with disabilities and building the capacity of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to become self advocates.  This would ensure meaningful and safe engagement of children with disabilities in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">relevant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">implementation and monitoring mechanisms.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.65pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Any post-2015 framework should include mechanisms to promote and e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nsure that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> above approaches</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are prioritised.  </span></p><h2 style="margin:10pt 0pt 0pt 28.8pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-28.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Within the scope of this Inquiry, we would highlight the following matters for the consideratio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">n of the Committee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.49pt; padding-left:14.21pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Whilst the progress so far in the post</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2015 negotiations is welcome, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">/UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should make clear how it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">intend</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to ensure that the post-2015 framework adequately reflects the needs of children [and adults] with disabilities?  We call on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to make a public pledge to include disabled children equitably in its work and to tie such a pledge into influencing the post</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> 2015 development programme.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.11pt; padding-left:14.59pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Support for a specific conditionality on the UK’s bilateral and multilateral international assistance would reflect the developed understanding that children with disabilities are at increased risk of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">violence and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">harm through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> inappropriate forms of alternative care that are unable to meet their needs.  Such a conditionality would stipulate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that funding should only be used for appropriate community based services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and that funding should not be used to build or renovate institut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">children.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.99pt; padding-left:14.71pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use its position as a respected agency</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, which has played a key role in the post 2015 negotiations,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to advocate for an international moratorium on all aid spending o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n institutional systems of care and for a prioritisation o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f the family and community based alternatives that bett</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er serve the needs of the child.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 42.89pt; padding-left:13.81pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s own programmes, specific </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">indicators </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which monitor the impact on the most vulnerable children, including those with disabilities and in residential car</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> would help to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ensure adequate child protection methodology and processes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">’s work.  This would lead to better and measurable outcomes for disabled children.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 41.5pt; padding-left:15.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In line with the aforementioned statement by eminent UN experts in child protection o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f 20 November 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">it is vital that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the protection of the most vulnerable children including those with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and living in institutions, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is included in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">post 2015 development framework</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ow does </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> intend to support this process?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 56.7pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="margin:24pt 0pt 0pt 21.6pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">U</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">seful </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Resources</span></h1><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Common European Guidelines on the Transition from Institutional to Community Based Care</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><a href="http://www.deinstitutionalisatioguide.eu"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.deinstitutionalisatioguide.eu</span></a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ad Hoc Expert Group</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the Transition from Institutional to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Community Based Care. European Commission 2009 </span><a href="http://ec.europa.eu/social/main.jsp?langId=en&amp;catId=89&amp;newsId=614&amp;furtherNews=yes"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://ec.europa.eu/social/main.jsp?langId=en&amp;catId=89&amp;newsId=614&amp;furtherNews=yes</span></a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Lancet Global Health, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Vol. 1, Issue 4, October 2013: Inclusive nutrition for children and adults with disabilities, Groce et al</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><a href="http://www.thelancet.com/journals/langlo/article/PIIS2214-109X(13)70056-1/fulltext"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.thelancet.com/journals/langlo/article/PIIS2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">214-109X(13)70056-1/fulltext</span></a></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">einstitutionalisation – A Human Rights Priority for Children with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">”.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Georgette Mulheir </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Equal Rights Review, Volume 9 – 2012  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><a href="http://www.equalrightstrust.org/ertdocumentbank/err9_full.pdf"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://ww</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">w.equalrightstrust.org/ertdocumentbank/err9_full.pdf</span></a></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">“Out from the Shadows – sexual violence against children with disabilities.” Save the Children (2011) </span><a href="http://www.savethechildren.org.uk/sites/